body:
Environment:
LibGDX: LATEST from master branch on Github as of 18-Feb-2017
IntelliJ IDEA IDE Community Edition 
Java: jdk1.8.0_102
Gradle Source Compatibility = 1.8

The issue is related to which constructor overload is used in Animation.java. The constructor that takes a var-arg parameter works correctly (no issue with type erasure), but the other constructors that take an Array object demonstrate the issue shown below.

I took the latest source of LibGDX and the following sample demonstrates the bug (related to type erasure):

The existing test class that was modified: 
\libgdx\tests\gdx-tests\src\com\badlogic\gdx\tests\AnimationTest.java

Changes to two methods:

```
import com.badlogic.gdx.utils.Array;
@Override
public void create () {
	texture = new Texture(Gdx.files.internal("data/walkanim.png"));

	Array<TextureRegion> leftWalkFrames = new Array<>();
	leftWalkFrames.addAll(TextureRegion.split(texture, 64, 64)[0]);

	Array<TextureRegion> rightWalkFrames = new Array<>(leftWalkFrames.size);

	for (int i = 0; i < rightWalkFrames.size; i++) {
		TextureRegion frame = new TextureRegion(leftWalkFrames.get(i));
		frame.flip(true, false);
		rightWalkFrames.set(i, frame);
	}
	leftWalk = new Animation<>(0.25f, leftWalkFrames);
	rightWalk = new Animation<>(0.25f, rightWalkFrames);

	cavemen = new Caveman[100];
	for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++) {
		cavemen[i] = new Caveman((float)Math.random() * Gdx.graphics.getWidth(),
			(float)Math.random() * Gdx.graphics.getHeight(), Math.random() > 0.5 ? true : false);
	}
	batch = new SpriteBatch();
	fpsLog = new FPSLogger();
}

@Override
public void render () {
	Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);
	batch.begin();
	for (int i = 0; i < cavemen.length; i++) {
		Caveman caveman = cavemen[i];

		TextureRegion frame = null;

		if(caveman.headsLeft){
			frame = leftWalk.getKeyFrames()[0];
		}else{
			frame = rightWalk.getKeyFrames()[0];
		}
		batch.draw(frame, caveman.pos.x, caveman.pos.y);
	}
	batch.end();

	for (int i = 0; i < cavemen.length; i++) {
		cavemen[i].update(Gdx.graphics.getDeltaTime());
	}

	fpsLog.log();
}
```

Runtime exception and stack Trace:

> :tests:gdx-tests-jglfw:classes
> java.lang.ClassCastException: [Ljava.lang.Object; cannot be cast to [Lcom.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.TextureRegion;
> 	at com.badlogic.gdx.tests.AnimationTest.render(AnimationTest.java:95)
> 	at com.badlogic.gdx.backends.jglfw.JglfwApplication.render(JglfwApplication.java:270)
> 	at com.badlogic.gdx.backends.jglfw.JglfwApplication$2.windowRefresh(JglfwApplication.java:157)
> 	at com.badlogic.jglfw.GlfwCallbacks.windowRefresh(GlfwCallbacks.java:45)
> 	at com.badlogic.jglfw.Glfw.glfwPollEventsJni(Native Method)
> 	at com.badlogic.jglfw.Glfw.glfwPollEvents(Glfw.java:793)
> 	at com.badlogic.gdx.backends.jglfw.JglfwInput.update(JglfwInput.java:140)
> 	at com.badlogic.gdx.backends.jglfw.JglfwApplication.frame(JglfwApplication.java:221)
> 	at com.badlogic.gdx.backends.jglfw.JglfwApplication.start(JglfwApplication.java:200)
> 	at com.badlogic.gdx.backends.jglfw.JglfwApplication.initialize(JglfwApplication.java:180)
> 	at com.badlogic.gdx.backends.jglfw.JglfwApplication$1.run(JglfwApplication.java:89)
> 	at java.lang.Thread.run(Thread.java:745)
> :tests:gdx-tests-jglfw:launchTestsJglfw

The line referenced in the stack trace (AnimationTest.java:95) is:
`     frame = leftWalk.getKeyFrames()[0];`
	
The issue is in a constructor in Animation.java:
```
public Animation (float frameDuration, Array<? extends T> keyFrames) 
{
...
		T[] frames = (T[]) new Object[keyFrames.size];
...
}
```

One fix could be to support passing the type as a parameter to the constructor as Tom-Ski noted.
